Abstract:The Research reported here is primarily
concerned with the development and application of
high speed/VLSi intelligent binary transducers,
bioelectrodes to detect low pressure and current
changes. These biomolecular information processing
elements (biosensors) can be directly installable
devices in vocal organs and in some possible places
of articultion to study the biomechanism of speech.
These transducers allows the data acquisition
facilities for parallel processing computers and
knowledge based on intelligent speech recognition
system.
1.INTRODUCTION
Speech recognition is a primary goal of fifth
generation computers. This is a multi disciplinary
field and applications are in vast area. A branch
of artificial intelligence is dealing for with this
problem last three decades. Looking at the state of
art in the published literature it is found that
speech recognition is very difficult. In early
speech recognition researches it is assumed that all
information needed
to
recognize the utterance was
present in speech waveform only. But recent
understanding reveal that there are many periods
during an utterance, when the word being spoken are
not clearly recognizable in the waveform. A wide
variety of knowledge must be bought to bear during
the peceptual process in order to understand what
has been spoken. Such a complete understanding
system does not seems to be realizable now.
L1-91
In this paper we propose a VLSI intelligent
transducers design methodology and implementation
techniques. These transducers are biocompatible and
are directly interefaced with parallel processing
computers using artificial intelligence approach.
We made an attempt using above mentioned
bioelectrodes and advanced microprocessors to
understand the biomechanism
of:
speech.
1I.ACOUSTICAS OF THE SPEECH MECHANISM
The acoustical principles involved in the
operation of both the sound source in the larynx and
filtering system
of
the vocal track.
Speech is caused by excitation of the vocal
cavities with acoustic stimuli. The vocal cavities
forms a linear system having a number of damped
resonances. The excitation is provided by larynx in
the form of recurrent series of impulsive shocks and
also by turbulent flow through the restricted
passages.
